post_text:
*** Dr. Silvernell Update ***

To All,

We are eagerly awaiting the startup of our new school year. As we move forward, and new information is coming out we are altering a few things we have previously shared.

New scientific studies and local events have prompted us to revisit our mask policy here at CCS. When we reopen, the expectation for our children is to keep their masks on at all times unless otherwise instructed by the teacher. The scientific evidence shows that this is one of the best practices to prevent the spread of COVID, and other illnesses. We are asking the teachers to provide regular mask breaks for the children each period of the day.

Also, In order to help prepare our teachers better for a new mode of instruction, we have added a superintendentâ€™s conference day on September 9 for professional development purposes. This means that the first day for students will be Thursday, September 10. We are excited to reengage with our children.

Please enjoy the remainder of your summer and keep yourselves safe.

Sincerely,
Dr. Silvernell

Sincerely,
Dr. Silvernell

Cambridge graduates spotlighted in first drive-in theater graduation

post_text:
TONIGHT'S GRADUATION IS AT HATHAWAY'S DRIVE IN THEATER.

IMPORTANT REMINDERS:

Gates open: At Hathaways at 7:30 pm. This is the earliest you can get into the drive in theater.

Parking is a first come, first served basis for the car with the graduate in it.

The additional car(s) for your family members will be placed further back so that ALL GRADUATES ARE PARKED TOGETHER.

Additional cars are also first come first serve, so the earlier they arrive, the closer they will be to the twin screen.

We have to maintain social distancing protocols. Wear your masks if you exit your car and please do not sit outside of your car.

GRADUATES- BRING YOUR CAPS AT LEAST!
There is part of the ceremony where you will move your tassel over to the side, thus signifying you are, indeed, a high school graduate!!

DO NOT FORGET YOUR CAR PARKING PASSES. IF THE CAR DOES NOT HAVE A PARKING PASS IT WILL NOT BE ALLOWED TO ENTER.

shared_text:
Beth Hanno O'Grady
June 10 at 5:29 PM Â·

The Albany Business Review ranked Cambridge Central School #14 (out of the 84 schools in the region that were ranked). Seven of the schools in the top 14 are "low" needs while Cambridge is "average" needs. Needs are defined as a district's ability to meet the needs of its students with local resources. In terms of expenditures per student, CCS is ranked at #37 (out of 90) So, 36 schools spend more per student. The highest being Edinburg at $51,197 and lowest being Hudson Falls at $18,160 per student. Cambridge is ranked within a clump of 10 schools that expend between 25 and 26K per student. CAMBRIDGE STRONG thanks to a tight knit, caring community, dedicated teachers/administrators and hardworking staff. Thanks to all the volunteers too!

PLEASE NOTE: This message has updated information since the original post of Monday, June 1.

Absentee ballots have been mailed and are expected to arrive in your home beginning Wednesday, June 3.

Given the extremely short turn-around time to produce the ballots, the company supplying the ballots has been inundated by multiple school districts, thus causing a delay.

To ensure ballots are received by the June 9 deadline, the district is accepting the return of ballots through the secure night deposit box at the District Office, located 58 South Park Street. The deposit slot is located to the right of the door upon entering. Residents may return their ballots between now and 5:00 p.m. on Tuesday, June 9, 2020.

If you do not receive your ballot by Wednesdayâ€™s mailing, please call Kate Canini at 518-677-2653 ext. 1010 to obtain one.

The second round of new packets will be delivered tomorrow Monday, May, 4 throughout the day. We are looking to collect the previous week's work (round 1 of new instruction). Please place the completed work in the envelope it came from and either leave it by the mailbox or give it to the delivery person when they arrive. If you no longer have the envelope you can put it in a gallon zip lock bag or other bag. This work will be reviewed by teachers and help them give some feedback to students.

PLEASE NOTE: This only applies to students who cannot submit work via email or Google Classroom.

Thank you to all the parents, caregivers, and families for the hard work you are putting in at home.

Village of Cambridge NY
April 29 at 1:24 PM Â·

CAMBRIDGE FREE MASK GIVEAWAY SATURDAY MAY 2 FROM 10-12 AT CAMBRIDGE CENTRAL SCHOOL

The Village of Cambridge, Town of White Creek, Town of Cambridge, Town of Jackson in cooperation with the Cambridge Valley Chamber of Commerce, Cambridge Central school, and Washington County Department of Public Safety and Public Health Department, will be giving away free cloth face coverings from 10 to 12 on Saturday, May 2 at the Cambridge Central school.

The county received a supply of cloth face coverings from the US Department of Health and Human Services through New York State. The coverings are washable T-shirt type material, manufactured by HanesBrands, made of 100% cotton, in individually wrapped packages of five.

SUNY is excited to announce their first ever virtual college fairs on Thursday, May 14 from 3p-7p and Saturday, May 16 from 1p-6p! The fair will include representatives from nearly every SUNY campus. During the fair students will be able to communicate with campus representatives using text and video chat.

This is a unique opportunity to explore all of the opportunities at The State University of New York: challenging academics; innovative research; global study; and financial support.

We hope your juniors and their families will attend. Please register at https://www.suny.edu/attend/events/virtual-college-fair/

shared_text:
Cambridge Central School added 21 new photos.
March 28 at 4:30 PM Â·

So far, our amazing team has provided 692 meals per day, 7 days per week for a total. of 4,844 meals; serving 346 students and 148 families. Though the numbers are impressive, it's about the people; and without people we wouldn't be able to reach these numbers of people.

Also, if you've enjoyed any of the lettuce served this week, then you've consumed part of the first cop grown in the school. A few weeks ago the school obtained a Farmshelf indoor growing system as part of a farm to table initiative. Please watch for a future story about this.

Our tech team did an incredible job working out a process to distribute Chromebooks to our students twill be available for distribution on Monday (3/30) and Tuesday (3/31) from 9am-12 noon at the auditorium entrance.

None of this could be accomplished without the collaboration and innovation of our amazing team. #wearecambridge #letslead #stillworking #stillsmiling

There is a now a section on the school's website (cambridgecsd.org) where information regarding COVID-19 (Coronavirus) can be found. On the home page it is located under the "Spotlight" section and under the tab titled "COVID-19 Information & Updates." (Both areas have the same information).

There is now a letter on website (also coming home with students) regarding school events and activities. PLEASE NOTE: Because the information has been constantly changing, the district will not be posting the updates on social media. We want our community to have the LATEST information, and you are probably already aware that the way information is served on Facebook walls and other platforms are not always in chronological order. However, there will be notices indicating when new information is posted.

The week of February 3 - 7 is "Pride in Food Service Week."

The Association of Nutrition and Foodservice Professionals (ANFP) has designated this week to applaud food service professionals for their hard work and dedication to the job.

We'd like to show our fantastic cafeteria team our appreciation for the delicious and nutritious meals they plan prepare for us throughout the school year. They also go the extra mile in contracting with local food sources whenever possible.

Please have a heart and write a message of appreciation. The messages will be displayed in our cafeteria throughout the week. Click the link for a printer-friendly heart template: https://www.cambridgecsd.org/cms/lib/NY02212078/Centricity/Domain/8/heart.pdf

post_text:
Mrs. Toleman's sixth grade science class has been studying atmospheric pressure and weather maps. Steve LaPointe, a meteorologist from WRGB Channel 6, came to present information on winter weather patterns and how science is used to predict weather. He discussed the unique patterns we see in our area of the state and how some of the physical features of the area impact the weather. Students also enjoyed hearing about how the weather is broadcasted and the work that goes into it. This was a great opportunity for students to ask questions and learn about a science related career.

Thank you Steve LaPointe!!!

post_text: A big THANK YOU to Katherine Danforth, Administrative and Artistic Associate at Hubbard Hall. On January 13, she visited the 3rd and 4th grade Odyssey of the Mind teams to share acting tips with them, which included voice projection, diction, dramatic movement, and improvisation. These skills will come in handy when the teams compete at the regional WSWHE BOCES Odyssey of the Mind on Saturday, February 29. The competition will be held at Queensbury Middle School and the public is invited to attend. Hubbard Hall is one of the district's many strategic planning partners.

Cambridge Central School added 28 new photos.
December 16, 2019 at 4:21 PM Â·

On Monday, December 16, our elementary students learned about snow and winter safety. They were visited by Phil Spiezio, Greg Toleman, Tom Gray, and Drew Shaw of the Washington County Department of Public Works. They discussed snow and winter safety which included NOT digging tunnels or making snow forts, wearing bright colors, letting an adult know when playing outside and using the buddy system, staying away from the road, being mindful of flying debris from snow plows, the limited sight lines of snow plow drivers, and more. A big thank you to the crew for teaching our students about snow and winter safety

post_text: Last week the Tri-County School Nutrition Directors hosted a Student Food Show at the Elks Lodge in Greenwich. Over 15 vendors and 11 school school districts participated. The CCS Student Council representatives attended the show with the purpose of sampling locally produced food products, and to provide their feedback on which items they would like to see offered in the school cafeteria. The students also received nutrition education materials.
